    <title>Combined summary - Suggestion for a universal bitcoin value scale</title>
    <updated>2023-06-13T14:10:54.789766+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2018-August/016313.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Martin Damgaard suggested a universal bitcoin value color scale to tackle the decimal problem identified by BIP 176 in an email thread on the Bitcoin Protocol Discussion. However, Karl-Johan Alm pointed out that such a system could potentially be a new attack vector. Martin retracted his initial suggestion after receiving feedback from the group and realizing the immature nature of his suggestion. Adán Sánchez de Pedro Crespo suggested that Martin submit his work as a markdown document published somewhere with version control, such as GitHub, to make it easier for others to contribute. Martin has since created a GitHub version of his suggestion and collected the commons made to the first version in a remarks-file. He plans to create a new version incorporating the different commons and welcomes any help from interested contributors. The context discusses the use of colors in user experience (UX) design and their expected meanings. Martin Damgaard's suggestion aims to address the issue of dealing with small amounts in the bitcoin denomination. However, the author of an email suggests using BIP76 (Bits Denomination) instead, which has been used successfully with people of varying levels of familiarity. Additionally, the author proposes writing the bitcoin denomination to 8 decimal places to improve readability more than color coding. Clark also shared his opinion on the use of Bitcoin on the street, emphasizing the importance of observing how local wallet software displays bitcoin amounts and letting the standards write themselves over time.</summary>
